A cryptocurrency is a digital form of money. They are digital assets created to be used to pay for goods and services. Cryptocurrencies can be used as a store of value, unit of account and medium of exchange. These digital assets are secured on a distributed ledger called the blockchain. The first cryptocurrency was Bitcoin which was introduced in a whitepaper by pseudonymous creator Satoshi Nakamoto. It was launched in 2009. The digital asset has since served as the benchmark crypto asset.","_crypto_faq_general_a2":"You can buy cryptocurrency in several ways. Once one user sends a cryptocurrency to another, cryptocurrency miners validate and then add the transaction to the blockchain. Each transaction is cryptographically encoded and validator nodes compete to solve this cryptographic puzzle. Once this happens, the receiver will see the funds in their wallet balance.","_crypto_faq_general_a4":"\u003ca title=\"\" href=\"https://www.investing.com/academy/crypto/bitcoin-mining/\"\u003eCrypto mining\u003c/a\u003e  is the process of securing and validating transactions on a blockchain network. The Proof-of-Work (PoW) is the first recognised mining protocol and requires validators to compete in solving complex mathematical equations. The miner who gets the correct response would be eligible to add the transactions to the network and as such, receive the block rewards - in the form of newly minted Bitcoins. PoW mining requires specialised and expensive mining hardware to pull off, and this equipment consumes more energy and is difficult to maintain.","_crypto_faq_general_a5":"Staking crypto entails locking up your crypto asset to secure a particular network. In comparison, assets like Bitcoin use the Proof-of-Work (PoW) model to validate and secure transactions on their network, while others like Cardano and Polkadot use the PoS model. Crypto staking is a great way to earn passive income, and it is also a more energy-efficient model to mine new coins for the network. Due to its consistent yields and low barrier to entry, many crypto exchanges now offer Staking-as-a-Service (SaaS) to their users.","_crypto_faq_general_a6":"Cryptocurrency gains value through adoption and market speculators. The long white candlestick is 'the mother' and the small candlestick is 'the baby'.\r\nIt signals that the current uptrend is losing strength. \r\n\u003cBR\u003eThe shadows of the second candlestick do not have to be contained within the first candle's body, though it's preferable if they are.\r\nThe Harami indicator should be confirmed with the next candlestick. \u003cBR\u003eThe Harami pattern is also the first two candlesticks of the Three Inside patterns.\r\nIt is not as significant reversal pattern as the Hanging Man or Engulfing.","_Pattern_HaramiCrossBearish_desc":"After a long white candlestick at the high end of an uptrend, a candlestick opens lower or at the previous candlestick's close, ends within the body of the first candlestick and signals that the current uptrend is losing strength.\r\nIt is more significant reversal pattern than the basic Harami Bearish. \r\n\u003cBR\u003eThe shadows of the second candlestick do not have to be contained within the first candle's body, though it's preferable if they are.\r\nThe second candlestick body can be either white or black.","_Pattern_idendicalThreeBlackCrows_desc":"During an uptrend, three black candlesticks occur, each with a close below the previous candle.\r\nEach candlestick opens within the body of the previous candle and closes near or at its lows.\r\nThis pattern suggests that the market has been at a high price for too long, and investors are beginning to compensate for it.\r\nIt is more significant if it appears after a mature advance.","_Pattern_kickingBearish_desc":"The first candle is a White Marubozu.
